<paragraph blockId="43.[151,545,618,644]" box="[151,545,618,644]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,545,618,644]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
3.9. 
<taxonomicName authority="Westwood, 1838" authorityName="Westwood" authorityYear="1838" box="[203,545,618,644]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Scaphurae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scaphurae Westwood, 1838</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="43" pageNumber="44" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="43.[151,1437,690,789]" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">
This group presents only the genus 
<taxonomicName box="[562,669,690,716]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Scaphura" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="43" pageNumber="44" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[562,669,690,716]" italics="true" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Scaphura</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with 11 species, restricted to the South American continent (Neotropical Region, Andean Region and South American Transition Zone). Seven species are currently recognized for 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,762,788]" name="Brazil" pageId="43" pageNumber="44">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, and here we recorded three species, including a possible new species to science.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
